            "title": "Tipping the scales",
            "abstract": "Scaling is carried out in underground mining to remove any loose rock. It is typically done after a blast, or when renovating old headings because of ground creep, and it increases safety by decreasing the chance of rock or roof falls. The geology and mining method influence how much scaling is necessary, and the choice of the correct scaling tool depends on rock and structural characteristics; the softer the rock the more scaling is necessary. Purpose-built scalers are the most suitable types of equipment as modified LHDs or drill jumbos do not work as well, do not have special features designed to protect the operator, and are less cost-efficient. Scaling can also be carried out remotely using equipment with mounted cameras. Scaling equipment is provided by Brokk, Breaker Technology, Getman, and JH Fletcher",
